On a good length on leg, Maharaj looks to defend but misses it and gets hit on the thigh pad.
Keshav Maharaj is the next batsman in.

OUT! Caught behind! Ben Stokes gets his second of the game. Better from Stokes here. He pitches the ball up outside off. De Kock lunges forward and looks to defend but the ball tails away just a tad and kisses the outside edge of Quinton's willow. There is an appeal from the keeper and Stokes but surprisingly it is not a loud one. The bigger surprise is de Kock does not wait for umpire's decision and starts walking. This is very good sportsmanship from de Kock. In the age of DRS you hardly see players being honest and walk away without the umpire raising their finger. End of another counter-attacking knock from de Kock. He has been taking on the charge but surprisingly it's the defensive stroke that he has been dismissed off in both the innings. The lack of enthusiasm and energy from England after picking up that wicket does not put up a good sign. The lead is 323 now.
Low full toss on middle, de Kock drives it back towards the bowler.
Length delivery on off, de Kock taps it to point.
Length delivery on middle, de Kock nudges it towards the leg side for a single.
Full delivery on off, Quinton drives it towards mid off.
Good length delivery on off, de Kock blocks it off the back foot.
Length delivery on off, Philander plays it towards covers for a run.
On a length on off, Philander taps it to point.
Outside off, Philander offers no shot to this one.
Bowls a bouncer, de Kock lets it sail through to the keeper.
Short and outside off, Quinton looks to drive but misses it.
On a good length on middle, Philander looks to defend but gets an inside edge on it. It goes towards fine leg. The batsmen take a run.
NO BALL! Stokes oversteps! Good length delivery on middle, Vernon blocks it off the back foot.
Length delivery on off, Philander taps it to point.
On a good length on off, Vernon defends it off the front foot.
Bowls a bouncer, Philander does well to duck under it.
Quinton de Kock seems to have gotten hurt on his finger off the last ball. The physio has been called into check.
On a good length on middle, de Kock looks to defend but gets hit on the gloves.
Full delivery on middle, de Kock drives it back towards the bowler.
On a good length on middle, de Kock blocks it off the front foot.
Good length delivery on off, de Kock blocks it off the front foot.
Full delivery on middle, Quinton drives it towards mid on.
Joe Root is back on the field. That is a good sign for the visitors.
On a good length on off, de Kock blocks it well.
On a good length on off, Vernon blocks it off the front foot.
FOUR! BEAUTIFUL! A half volley but still had to be put away! It is bowled outside off, Vernon drives it through covers for a boundary.
Good length delivery on off, Philander offers a forward defense on this one.
On a good length on off, Quinton looks to drive but gets an outside edge. It goes towards third man. The batsmen cross ends.
Good length delivery outside off, de Kock looks to go after it but misses it.
Full delivery on leg, Quinton looks to flick but gets hit on the pads.
On a good length on off, de Kock plays it towards point and takes a run.
Good length delivery on off, Philander looks to defend but gets an outside edge. It goes towards third man. The batsmen cross ends.
On a length on off, Vernon plays it towards point.
BEATEN! On a good length and outside off, Philander looks to defend but misses it.
Full delivery on off, de Kock drives it towards mid off where the fielder makes an excellent stop. The batsmen still take a single.
EDGY! Good length ball on off, Philander looks to defend but it goes off the outside edge past the diving second slip fielder. The third man fielder comes across and cleans it up. A single taken.
Outside off, de Kock offers no shot to this one.
On a good length on middle, Philander looks to defend but gets an inside edge on it. It goes towards the leg side. The batsmen take a single.
Bowls a bouncer, Philander does well to duck under it.
On a good length on off, Philander defends it off the front foot.
Full delivery on off, Philander drives it to covers.

FOUR! South Africa are off to a flurry here. They are wearing whites but playing like they are in colored clothes here. Stokes starts with a back of a length ball on off, Vernon gets on his back foot and pulls it over mid-wicket. The ball bounces inside the ropes and goes away to the fence.
Ben Stokes to bowl from the other end. 3-1-6-1 are his figures so far.
Good length ball outside off, Vernon pushes it to deep cover and crosses over for a single.
FOUR! What a shot that is! Anderson bowls a half-volley outside off, Philander leans forward and creams the drive through covers for a boundary. First one in this session.
Fullish outside off, Philander makes a leave to the keeper.
Full delivery on off, Philander pushes it to mid off.
Back of a length on middle, Vernon stands tall and blocks it out.
Starts with a good length ball on middle, Philander works it to mid-wicket.

We are all set to begin the second session! Quinton de Kock and Vernon Philander make their way to the middle. James Anderson will start for the visitors. South Africa lead by 300. How many more runs will they add?
... Day 3, Session 2 ...

So South Africa are head and shoulders ahead in this game. They already have a healthy lead but will look to add more and kill this game off. England are down but not completely out of it. If they can somehow get the remaining 3 wickets quickly then they certainly will think they still have a shot. What is in store for us in the second session? Join us after the break to find out.

It was a morning to forget for the tourists. Their bowlers were all over the place. They needed to get early wickets but failed in their pursuit to get rid of the nightwatchman. They have got three wickets with Jofra Archer picking up 2 and stand-in skipper, Ben Stokes getting 1 but they have been well below par. Illness to Joe Root and Jos Buttler has not helped their case as they look out of ideas out in the middle. The frustration in the English camp has been very much visible as Broad and Stokes got into an argument as well. The visitors need to find a way to get some inspiration and come back stronger in the second session.

A brilliant session for the hosts and they are completely in charge of this game here. Carrying a lead of 175, Rassie van der Dussen and nightwatchman Anrich Nortje took the game to the visitors. They added a 91-run stand with Rassie getting to his maiden Test 50. The partnership finally was broken as Rassie was caught in front of the stumps. Anrich Nortje, soon followed him and fell for a very well played 40. Pretorius too did not last long but Quinton de Kock came out with a plan. His plan was to treat this red ball as the white ball of T20 and his quickfire and unbeaten 30 has seen the lead swell up to 300. The hosts still have 3 wickets in hand and with de Kock still out in the middle, expect it to go up even higher.
Fullish delivery outside off, de Kock is happy to let the ball go to the keeper. LUNCH ON DAY 3.
Back of a length ball on middle, Philander works it to square leg and takes a single. The lead for South Africa is now 300.
On a length outside off, Philander shoulders arms to this one.
BEATEN! Excellent bowling from Stokes. Bowls a good length ball around off, Philander attempts to defend it but fails to get any bat on it.
Outside off, de Kock drives this uppishly to deep cover where the fielder collects it on the bounce.
Full delivery down the leg side, de Kock looks to flick it but misses it completely.
Length delivery outside off, Vernon looks to defend it inside the line of the stumps.
Short again from Jofra. Vernon sways away from it.
Full on off and middle, de Kock throws his bat at it but the ball goes off the inner half of his bat and the ball goes towards fine leg for one.
Slightly slower now from Archer. It is on a length around off, de Kock strokes it through covers and gets a couple.
Wide! Bouncer bounces too high. De Kock was ready to play the pull but he sees it is going well over his head so he backs out of it.
FOUR! Short and pulled with power. It is a knuckle ball and short outside off, de Kock pulls it with confidence and power through mid on for a boundary.

SIX! Blink of an eye and de Kock has reached 22 already. He has come out in T20 mode here. Back of a length on the pads, de Kock picks it and lofts it over fine leg for a maximum. There is a man there but he is as good a spectator as us.
EDGED AND FOUR! Philander is off the mark with a lucky boundary. On a length outside off, Philander looks to defend it but it goes off the outside edge through the gully region and into the fence.
Good length ball on off, Vernon defends it to mid on.
BOUNCER! It is bowled around middle, Philander ducks under it.
Full delivery outside off, Philander leaves this ball alone.
Vernon Philander walks out to bat next. He was the star with the ball in the first innings and he also did well with the bat. Can he hang in there with de Kock and take South Africa's lead over 320?

OUT! CAUGHT! Brilliant bowling from Stokes on his return to the attack.  Bowled a short one first up and then sets the batter up with a beautiful ball. Fullish delivery outside off, Pretorius looks to drive it off the front foot but it goes off the outside edge towards first slip. Dom Sibley stationed there takes a simple catch. England taking wickets in a heap here. Can they finish off the tail quickly?
Bowls a bouncer, Pretorius lets it sail through to the keeper.
Th standing skipper, Ben Stokes introduces himself into the attack. He has bowled only 1 over so far and that was a maiden.
On the pads, Pretorius flicks it fine down the leg side for a single.
Another punch off the back foot. This time it is through cover-point and gets a couple.
FOUR! Back of a length ball outside off, Pretorius is quick to lash onto it. He gets on his back foot and punches it through covers for a boundary.
Another bouncer from Jofra. DP sits under this as well.
Bouncer! Pretorius ducks under it.
Dwaine Pretorius is the next batsman in.

OUT! Caught! Finally, finally England have got rid of the nightwatchman. Calling him a nightwatchman just does not sound right anymore as he has played a very, very good innings here. Nortje misses out on a well deserved fifty but he has done more than enough here. Jofra's pace finally gets the better of Anrich Nortje. It is quick and on the pads, Nortje looks to flick but the ball kisses his willow and then lobs off his pad towards short leg. Substitute Zak Crawley there takes an easy catch to bring an end to a wonderful innings from Nortje. Yes he has not scored a ton or even a fifty but he has played a gem of a knock here and has taken the gas out of the England players. He walks off to an applause from the crowd. The lead now stands at 273!
FOUR! De Kock has come with an attacking intent. This is a beautiful shot. Full and outside off, de Kock leans forward and hammers the drive through covers for a boundary.
On a good length on off, de Kock defends it off the front foot.
On a length on middle, de Kock pushes it towards mid on.
Full delivery on middle, Quinton drives it back towards the bowler.
On a good length and outside off, de Kock looks to drive but misses it.
Short delivery on off, Nortje taps it towards point and takes a single.
Another short one down the leg side. De Kock throws his bat at it but misses it this time.

EDGED BUT SIX! Short again from Archer. De Kock goes for the pull but it goes off the upper half of his bat and sails over the fine leg fence for another biggie. Jofra has a smile on his face but he must be fuming from inside.
SIX! De Kock is off the mark with a bang! Bouncer around the eye line from Archer. De Kock gets on his back foot and hooks it with power and right off the meat over the fine leg fence for a maximum.
Archer misses his line and sprays it down the leg side.
Pacy length ball pitching on middle and leg. De Kock looks to defend but gets beaten by the pace and gets hit on the thigh pad.
The hero from the first innings, Quinton de Kock walks out to bat now. South Africa in a much better position than they were when he walked out to bat in the first innings.

OUT! Umpire's call it is and Rassie's good knock comes to an end. Full ball pitching on middle and swinging in. Rassie looks to play it across the line but misses. He misses and the ball hits him on his pad. The English players go up in a confident appeal and the umpire raises his finger. Van der Dussen takes it upstairs straightaway. Replay rolls in and Hawk Eye shows that the ball is just about clipping the leg pole. Rassie will have to walk back but he does not take the review with him.
Rassie van der Dussen has been adjudged LBW! He has taken it upstairs. The on-field call is out so even if the ball is clipping the stumps, he will have to continue his walk.
Good length ball on middle, Nortje defends it off the back foot to the bowler.
BOUNCER! WIDE! It is bowled around middle, Anrich does well to duck under it.
On middle and leg, Nortje looks to whip it but misses to get hit on the thigh pad. No harm done though.
Good length ball on off, Rassie defends it out.
OUCH! Short delivery around middle and leg, Nortje hops to fend it uncomfortably but gets hit on the gloves. It flies to third man and the batters take a single.
FOUR! Take that! Back of a length ball outside off, Nortje punches it off the back foot to the deep cover region for a boundary.

FIFTY! Maiden Test fifty for Rassie van der Dussen! Beautiful innings from the debutant. He has taken the Proteas to safer shores. Good length ball on off, van der Dussen defends it to point and takes a single to get to the milestone. Can he score a ton?
On a length and outside off, Anrich taps it through point. The batsmen pick up a couple.
Bowls a bumper outside leg, Nortje ducks underneath it.
Bowls a bouncer, Nortje ducks under it.
On a length on middle, Anrich flicks it to mid-wicket.
Bowls it down the leg side, Nortje looks to flick but misses it.
Full delivery on leg, van der Dussen flicks it through square leg for a run.

In the air... but safe. Another well directed bouncer from Broad! Anrich Nortje takes his eyes off and looks to defend. It lobs off his glove and falls short of the man running in from mid-wicket. That could have gone anywhere but the fortune England are having this morning it was always going to fall away from the fielders.
Bowls a short delivery down the leg side, Nortje looks to nudge but misses it.

That is got to hurt. Anrich Nortje has been hit on his rib, just over his chest guard. He is down in pain but he is a tough lad. The physio is out now with an ice pack. Alos the floodlights are on as it has gone dark here in Centurion.
Bowls short on the body, Nortje looks to defend but gets hit on the body.
BEATEN! Good length delivery outside off, Anrich looks to defend but misses it.
Short delivery on leg, Nortje defends it off the back foot.
Good length ball on middle, Rassie works it to deep square leg for a single.

FIVE WIDES! Poor keeping from Bairstow! Full delivery swinging away, outside off from the batsman, van der Dussen leaves it alone. Bairstow dives to his right to collect but fails to do so. The ball rolls to the third man fence.
Bowls again a short delivery, Nortje looks to defend but gets an outside edge. It goes towards point.
Length delivery outside off, Nortje taps it through point. The batsmen get two runs.
Bowls a quick short ball on middle, Nortje does well to defend it.
On a length on middle, Nortje nudges it towards the leg side.
Outside off, Anrich offers no shot to this one.
Joe Root is still off the field and is yet to come back. Stokes is the standing captain.
Length delivery on middle, van der Dussen flicks it through square leg for a run.

Drinks! An excellent hour of play for the Proteas. They have extended their lead to 236 and the overnight batsman of Rassie van der Dussen and Anrich Nortje are looking comfortable out there. England desperately need wickets otherwise the game will go away from them. Can they make their way back?
Beauty to end the over! Broad hits the deck hard and makes the ball shape away off the pitch. Nortje looks to defend but gets squared up.

Edged but safe again. Good length ball in the channel of uncertainty around off. Rassie looks to defend but the ball goes off the outside edge. He plays it with soft hands and hence the ball goes to the right of the man at slips on the bounce. He dives and tries to stop it but cannot do so cleanly and they steal a single. Much better from Broad.
FOUR! Exquisite cover drive from van der Dussen. Broad is once again guilty of overpitching it on off, van der Dussen gets on his front foot and plays a crispy drive through covers for a boundary.
Now shows calmness and leaves this length ball away from the off pole alone.
FOUR! This is right off the meat. Fuller on off, Rassie gets on his front foot and creams his drive through covers for a boundary.

EDGED AND FOUR! Runs starting to leak here. Full on off, van der Dussen looks to drive but the ball takes the outside edge and goes to the right of gully. Ben Stokes there dives on that side but the ball goes wide of him and to the fence.
Bouncer to end the over and once again Nortje sways away from it.
FOUR! Nortje winning the battle here against Jofra. Fuller on middle, Anrich drives it through mid on and fetches himself a boundary.

FOUR BYES! The pacy bouncer has beaten everyone. A very quick bouncer from Jofra. It is well directed as well. Nortje sways away from it. Bairstow behind the stumps stretches to his maximum but it goes over him and to the fence.
Good length delivery on off, Nortje keeps it out.
On a good length on off, van der Dussen taps it towards point and takes a single. 50-run stand between Rassie van der Dussen and Anrich Nortje.

NOT OUT! It is umpire's call on hitting the stumps. Good length ball on middle and leg, van der Dussen moves towards the offside and attempts to flick it. He gets hit on the pads. The England players appeal but the umpire shakes his head. Stokes, who is captaining in place of Root goes for the review. Hawk Eye rolls in and it shows that it is umpire's call on hitting the leg stump. England don't lose the review. The ball goes towards the leg side and the batters take two.
An LBW appeal has been taken upstairs. Rassie van der Dussen is the man in question. It looks close but the replays show that it is umpire's call on hitting the leg stump.
Full delivery on middle, Nortje flicks it through mid-wicket. The fielder in the deep does well to stop it. The batsmen pick up a couple.
On middle, Nortje keeps it out.
On a good length on middle, Anrich defends it off the back foot.
Good length delivery on off, Nortje blocks it off the front foot.
Outside off, Nortje offers no shot to this one.
On a good length on off, van der Dussen plays it towards mid off and takes a quick run.

Direct hit and it would have been close. Good length ball outside off, van der Dussen strokes it towards point and calls for a quick single. Denly gets to the ball and has a shy at the keeper's end but misses. So Jofra's first has been dealt with relative ease by the duo. England are lacking ideas here and this partnership is starting to not just annoy them but take the game away from them.
Length delivery around off, Nortje nudges it to point and gets a single.
Once again goes close to the body, Anrich defends it.
This one skids off the surface. Back of a length around off, Nortje looks to play it towards point but misses.
Archer goes full on off, Nortje pushes it to mid off like a proper batsman.
Archer starts with a back of a length ball outside off, Nortje guides it to the right of gully. The fielder dives and saves runs for his side.
Finally Archer is being brought into the attack for the first time today.
On a good length on off, Rassie taps it to point.
Good length delivery on middle, Rassie keeps it out.
On a good length on off, van der Dussen blocks it off the front foot.
Full delivery on off, Rassie drives it to mid off.
On a length on middle, Nortje flicks it towards square leg for a run.

Good length delivery on middle, Nortje defends it towards mid-wicket. Rassie sets off and comes halfway down the track but Nortje does well to send him back. The fielder goes for a direct hit at the bowler's end but misses it. Rassie van der Dussen would have been a goner.
Stuart Broad is into the attack. 5-2-6-1 are his figures.
On a good length on off, Nortje defends it towards the leg side and takes a quick single. Curran gets to the ball, picks it and goes for a direct hit at the bowler's end but misses it.
FOUR! Brilliant batting this! Nortje is batting like a proper batsman out there. Curran bowls a full delivery on middle, Anrich flicks this beautifully through mid-wicket for a boundary.
Length delivery on off, Nortje taps it to point.
On a good length on off, Anrich defends it off the front foot.
Full delivery on middle, Rassie drives it through mid on for a run.
Bowls a bouncer, van der Dussen lets it sail through to the keeper.
Full delivery on middle, Nortje flicks it to mid-wicket.
Bowls a bumper outside off, Nortje sways away from it.

FOUR! Edgy but Nortje and South Africa will take it. Back of a length ball on off, Nortje looks to defend but it goes off the outside edge through gully and into the fence. The lead is 200 for South Africa.
Bowls a bouncer outside off, Nortje sways away from it.
Outside off, Anrich offers no shot to this one.
Length delivery on middle, Rassie flicks it towards mid-wicket for a run.
EDGY FOUR! Valuable runs. Good length ball outside off, Nortje looks to drive it but takes the outside edge and goes through the vacant gully region for a boundary. The lead moves to 195 now.

Full delivery on leg, Nortje looks to flick but gets hit on the pads. The bowler appeals for lbw but the umpire shakes his head. Bairstow, the keeper is seen signaling to the bowler that it is drifting down.
Bowls a bouncer, Nortje ducks under it.
On a good length on off, Nortje blocks it off the front foot.
Good length delivery on leg, Nortje looks to flick but gets an inside edge onto the pads.
On a good length on off, Nortje looks to defend but gets an outside edge. It goes towards the slip region on one bounce.
Length delivery on middle, Nortje nudges it towards square leg for a run.
BEATEN AGAIN! Good length delivery outside off, Nortje looks to defend but misses it.
BEATEN! On a good length and outside off, Nortje looks to defend but misses it.
Bowls a bouncer, Nortje lets it sail through to the keeper.
Full delivery on middle, van der Dussen flicks it through wide mid on. The fielder from wide long on does well to stop it before the ropes. The batsmen get three runs.
Outside off, van der Dussen shoulders arms to this one.

NOT OUT! Nortje survives. It has gone off the shoulder! Excellent review from Nortje and South Africa. This though was a snorker of a delivery from Sam Curran. He bowls a short of a length ball around off, Nortje hops to defend but it seemed to have taken the outside edge of the bat. The England players put in an appeal immediately and the finger goes up. Nortje has reviewed it immediately and it is proved to be an excellent review. The Ultra Edge shows that it has not gone off the bat but has taken the shoulder and gone into the mitts of the keeper.

Anrich Nortje has been caught behind but he has taken the review straightaway. There was a definite noise but Nortje going upstairs straightaway indicates that the ball has hit him on his shoulder. Replay rolls in and it looks like it has hit his back shoulder. Ultra Edge comes next and it confirms that there was nothing as the ball goes past the bat it hit his shoulder.
On a good length on off, Nortje defends it off the front foot.
Full delivery on off, van der Dussen drives it towards mid off for a run.
Good length delivery on off, Rassie keeps it out.
Length delivery on off, Nortje taps it through point for a single.
On a good length on off, van der Dussen guides it towards third man for a run.
On middle, Nortje defends it back.
Fullish on off, van der Dussen drives it towards cover for a single.
Defended off the front foot by the batsman presenting the full face of the bat.
Good length ball outside off, Nortje whips it to the leg side for a single.

Poor running! Almost threw his wicket there does Rassie van der Dussen! Back of a length delivery on off, Rassie defends it to cover and calls for a quick single. Sibley comes after it, slides and throws it at the bowler's end. He misses. Had he hit, van der Dussen would have been well out. This is not how Rassie would want to get out as he has got himself in on this difficult pitch. Lucky that Sibley missed the stumps.
Good length delivery on middle, Rassie defends it to point.
BEATEN! Beautiful piece of bowling from Curran! Full delivery outside off, Nortje looks to drive it but fails to get any bat on it.
On middle and leg,  Anrich pushes it to mid on.
Good length on off, Nortje defends it out.
Fuller outside off, Nortje drives it through covers and picks up a couple before Sibley can come across and clean it up.
Good length delivery on off, Rassie defends it towards mid off and calls Nortje for a quick single. The fielder has a shy at the keeper's end but misses. Nortje was well in though.
Fullish on off, van der Dussen pushes it to mid off.
BEATEN! Good length ball outside off, Nortje looks to defend it off the back foot but the ball whizzes past his bat and into the mitts of the keeper.
Full delivery on middle, Rassie works it to the leg side for a single.
On off, pushed to point.

OHH! Rassie makes a risky leave! Good length ball around off tailing in, van der Dussen chooses to leave it but gets hit on the pads. The England players appeal but nothing from the umpire. They opt not to go for the review. Good decision in the end as the Hawk Eye later on shows that it was missing the off stump.
Good length ball on middle and leg, van der Dussen works it to mid-wicket.
Fullish delivery on middle, Rassie flicks it to deep square leg and Sam Curran comes across from fine leg and makes a good diving stop. Two taken.
James Anderson will bowl from the other end. 4-0-19-1 are his figures so far.
BEATEN! Curran bowls a full delivery outside off, Nortje attempts to drive it but fails to put any bat on it.
BEATEN! Beautiful delivery! On a length outside off, Nortje attempts to defend it but fails to get any bat on it.
Full delivery on off angling into the batsman, Anrich blocks it out.
Good length on off, Nortje defends it to mid off off the back foot.
On a length outside off, Anrich shoulders arms to this one.
Starts with a full delivery outside off, Nortje lets the ball go to the keeper.
Sam Curran to start the proceedings for England. 4-2-8-0 are his figures so far. He has been the best bowler for England in the first innings.

Meanwhile, Jos Buttler has gone down with a bug and Jonny Bairstow will be taking the gloves for the time being. We are ready to begin Day 3. The England players are out in the middle. Rassie van der Dussen and Anrich Nortje will resume their innings for the hosts.

175 is the lead for South Africa at the moment. They bowled brilliantly in England's first innings, bowling them out for a paltry 181. In return they lost 4 wickets but still remain on top in this Test match. Aiden Markram has been ruled out of the series due to a fractured finger. The visitors are not out of this yet and if they can pick up the remaining wickets quickly and restrict the lead to around 225, they will feel that they are still in with a chance. Jofra Archer was the pick of the bowlers for England, picking up 2 wickets while Broad and Anderson picked 1 each. The first session will dictate terms because if South Africa can survive that, the lead might swell up to 250 and that will not be easy to chase. Can the visitors make a comeback in this game or will the Proteas continue to be on top? Join us in a while to find out.
... Day 3, Session 1 ...

So that is it from exciting Day 2. We now move to Day 3 which can not just be a crucial day but it also has the potential to be the final day of this Test. It is not an easy wicket to bat on and at this point of time the hosts are on top. But if England can manage to wrap them up under the lead of 250 then it will certainly be game on. Who will dominate Day 3? Join us on Saturday, 28th December 2019 to find out. The play begins at 1000 Local (0800 GMT). Till then, cheers!

England came back stronger in the day with the ball. Having given a big advantage to the hosts, England needed to strike early and they did coup 3 early blows. Faf du Plessis and Rassie van der Dussen counter-attacked and ensured that the lead went past 150 with 7 wickets in hand. Skipper Faf du Plessis surrendered in his counter-attack. Rassie and nightwatchman Anrich Nortje then added 10 runs and ensured they see off the day with the hosts potential 175/4.

Another falter with the bat saw England lose the grip of the game. At one stage they were on top of the match but once again their batting crumbled like a cookie and from 142/3 the visitors bundled out for an under-par score of 181, giving the hosts a big lead. No one apart from Denly, Root, Stokes and Curran could manage to score more than 20 and that led to the tourists downfall.

After batting for just under 10 minutes early on in the day, the hosts did an impeccable job with the ball. The bowling led by Vernon Philander's 4-fer wrapped up the visitors for a paltry score of 181 giving them a lead of 103. Philander was well supported by Rabada, Nortje and Pretorius who scalped 3, 2 and 1 wicket respectively.

Another eventful day of Test match cricket comes to an end. A day that belonged to the bowlers. 15 wickets have fallen on the day. A look at the scorecard and one would feel South Africa are struggling at 72/4 but add that 103-run lead and the scorecard reads 175/4 and you would realize it is the hosts who are on top of this game.
Good length ball angled into the batter, van der Dussen keeps it out. THAT WILL BE STUMPS ON DAY 2.
In the channel outside off, it is left alone.
Another bouncer. It is outside off, van der Dussen lets it pass to the keeper.
This is sprayed down the leg side now. Rassie lets it be.
Bouncer outside off, it is left alone.
On the pads, worked towards square leg.
Ben Stokes replaces Sam Curran. For the first time in this game Stokes is having a go with the ball.

A dipping full toss. It is around the body. Nortje ducks under it. The square leg umpire signals it as no ball but Jofra is upset. He puts a very valid argument that the ball was dipping and the umpires after having a brief chat decide that they'll let that one pass. Lucky escape for Archer as that might have been end of his action with the ball.
No Ball! Maybe the ball slipped out of Jofra's hand there. Knuckle ball but it goes wrong and it ends up being a beamer. Nortje ducks under it.
Pacy and on top of middle. Anrich moves away and keeps his bat hanging. The ball hits the inner half of his bat.
Back of a length on the body. Anrich does well to defend it.
On the body, Rassie flicks it to the on side and gets a single.
FOUR! Poor ball from Jofra. Full on the pads, Rassie flicks it with ease through mid-wicket for a boundary.
Around off, it is defended.
FOUR! Full ball outside off, Nortje goes for the drive this time and connects it nicely. It races between point and gully and into the third man fence.
Good length ball around off and middle, Nortje keeps it out.
Superb bouncer but Nortje does well to duck under it. A bouncer aimed at the head of the batter there.
Good length delivery outside off, Anrich shoulders arms to it.
Length delivery away from off, Nortje does not go after it.
Full on off, Nortje defends it off the front foot and keeps that one out.
In the channel outside off, van der Dussen looks to defend initially but pulls his bat away at the very last moment.
Shortish and around off, it is blocked off the back foot.

What a snorter this one! Brilliant brilliant stuff from Archer. He seems to have found his mojo for now. Bangs this one short around off, van der Dussen initially looks to defend but seeing the bounce on this one, tries to sway away. He ends up doing that well. Buttler behind the wicket makes a loud appeal but Archer goes up only after seeing Buttler appeal. The umpire shows no interest and England skipper does not opt for the review either.
Good length ball around off, van der Dussen keeps it out.
Another bouncer on middle, Rassie does well to sway away.
Short ball down the leg side. Van der Dussen lets it be. De Kock does well to dive to his left and pouch the ball.
Full and on middle, Nortje defends it back to the bowler.
Full toss outside off, Nortje lets it be.
Around off on a good length, this time Nortje pushes it towards cover.
Snorter now! Curran bends his back and bangs this one short around off. He has Nortje fending it off his toes but luckily for Nortje, the ball misses everything and goes in the mitts of the keeper.
Fuller and outside off once again, Nortje does not offer any shot again.
Curran goes full outside off to Nortje first up. He lets it be.

Huge appeal for caught behind but the umpire says no. Good length ball pitching around off, Rassie looks to defend away from the body. There is a noise as the ball goes past the bat. Jofra initially does not think there is bat involved but he sees Root go up so even he does. Jofra thinks he has his man but Buttler does not believe it. Root, Archer and Jos have a brief chat but Buttler is sure there is nothing on it. Root goes with his keeper's gut and does not opt for a review. Good decision from Root to back his keeper's thought as Ultra Edge later on rolls in and it shows no spike as the ball goes past the bat.
Bouncer! Rassie ducks under it.
South Africa have sent a nightwatchman as Anrich Nortje comes in next.

OUT! Caught! Faf du Plessis holes out! England fans, England fans, England fans. Wherever you are, please stand up and applaud. Not Jofra Archer. Not Sam Curran. But Nasser Hussain. His constant praise about Faf playing the pull shot has actually jinxed the Protea skipper. 'He will let the short ball go if he is playing for the World XI. But he can also play the pull shot while featuring in the World XI.' He mentioned this twice in the span of 5 minutes and it has worked. The jinx. The trick. Either ways, if you live by the sword, you need to be prepared to die by it as well. The ploy to go after Archer has backfired. Could du Plessis have held himself back in these final few minutes? But then, when you are in overdrive, it is very difficult to get back into first gear. And that is exactly what has transpired. Quick and back of a length delivery on middle, Faf instinctively goes for the pull but takes his eyes off the ball. He is on a knee while trying to pull that. That looks good in T20s or while featuring in the death overs of an ODI innings. But in this format, it seems pretty audacious, to be honest. And invitation of extreme criticism if you fail to pull it off. Faf is not in control while playing the pull and as a result, the ball hits the top half of his bat. It is not cleanly struck and the ball goes towards deep backward square leg. Sam Curran comes running in from fine leg and takes a good catch. Faf shakes his head while smiling at the same time. Big mistake. Jofra wins the battle. Just conceded a few runs in the process but he has got his side in a realistic chance to win this game now. 165/4 is the effective score. If the lead can be restricted to 225, this could be a cracker of a finish.

In the air and safe! Short ball from Archer. It gets quickly onto Rassie. He looks to pull but it goes off the upper half of the bat. It lobs towards the no man's land at mid-wicket and they take a single.
FOUR! Pulled with power and disdain. The South Africans have decided to take on Archer here. Back of a length on off, Rassie pulls it through mid-wicket for a boundary.
Fuller on middle and off, Rassie flicks it through mid-wicket for one.
Full and going away from the right-hander from middle and off. Du Plessis plays it against the swing and tucks it to mid-wicket.
Very good ball. Yorker outside off. Faf looks to play it on the off side but it goes off the inside edge down to the leg side.
Full on off, du Plessis pushes it to mid off.
This one comes in. It is full outside off, Faf hits it back towards the bowler off the inner half of his bat.
Full on off, Faf flicks it to square leg.
Good length ball on off, du Plessis defends it off the front foot.
Good length delivery around off, it zips in. Faf taps it down towards third man and gets a single to get through the over.

SIX! Faf has just gone after the bouncer here and got out of it getting the maximum result. Bouncer from Archer, Faf gets on his back foot and pulls it with confidence and power over the square leg fence for a biggie.
Fuller on off, du Plessis pushes it to cover.
Back of a length on off, Faf punches it towards mid off.
Length delivery on top of the stumps. Du Plessis defends it back to the bowler.
Good length ball on middle and it comes back in. Faf tucks it to square leg.
The batsman shows the full face of the bat and defends the ball off the back foot.

NOT OUT! Just short of Stokes at second slip, so the on-field umpire's decision will be overturned. Curran's celebrations will be short-lived. But a brilliant delivery. It is a fullish ball around off, van der Dussen looks to defend but the ball moves away and takes a thick outside edge. It goes to the left of Ben Stokes at second slip who dives to his left for the catch and Curran celebrates. But Stokes is not sure if that is a clean one though as he gives a wry smile. Rassie is very much sure that he is not out and shakes his head. However, the umpires get together and refer it upstairs with the soft signal as OUT! Here come the replays. The first look indicates that the ball bounces just before it goes in the hand of Stokes there. The second look, the side-on one, shows some doubt. The third umpire is checking various angles. They are taking their time and now they confirm it to be short of Stokes, so van der Dussen survives.

EDGED AND TAKEN! Or is it? Has that been taken cleanly? Stokes has taken a very low catch in the slips. He does not look that confident but does not deny that the catch was taken either. The on-field umpires have gone upstairs with the soft signal as OUT! Let's see what the replays have to say. Clear BOUNCE. Guess Stokes knew that the ball had not gone straight into the hands. As a fielder, you know when the ball goes straight in. The first replay, the front on one, shows the ball landed in front. However, looking at the side on angle, it is not exactly clear. Surely, when in doubt, go with the batsman. Not just umpire's call. Rassie can stay.
Good length ball on off, van der Dussen taps it towards point.
In the channel outside off, it is left alone.
Landed on middle, du Plessis works it behind square leg for a run.
Curran starts with a fuller ball outside off, Rassie drives it through covers and before the mid off fielder can get to the ball, van der Dussen takes three.
Sam Curran to have a go with the ball for the first time in this innings after the break. He was very impressive in the first innings and finished with a 4-fer. Can he repeat his heroics?

Drinks Break! England have bowled well now and have put presssure on South Africa by taking three wickets. On the other hand, the hosts would look to increase their lead and would want a big partnership from here.

FOUR! Third boundary of the over and it is a very good over for the Proteas. Length ball delivery outside off. Faf likes the width on offer and he gets on his back foot and cuts it through point for a boundary.
Now once again shows calmness and defends this length delivery astutely.
FOUR! Crunched away! Length ball away from off, du Plessis shows aggressive approach and slashes this through covers for a boundary.
Back of a length on off, Faf defends this off his back foot.
FOUR! Driven crisply! Slightly overpitched on off, du Plessis is onto it in a flash and creams his drive through covers for a boundary.
Back of a length on the body, van der Dussen flicks it to square leg for a single.
Very full on off. Almost a yorker, Faf does well to defend.
Length delivery outside off, Faf shoulders arms to it.
The batsman chooses to leave the ball outside his off stump.
On a good length on middle, du Plessis keeps it out.
Good length delivery outside off, du Plessis defends it off the front foot.
On a good length on off, Rassie defends it towards the off side and takes a quick single.
End of a very eventful over from Archer. A boundary and a wicket of it.
Length delivery outside off, Faf leaves it alone.
Good length ball outside off. Rassie leaves it alone. The ball dies on its way to the keeper so Buttler misses it and it goes past him and they steal a bye.
Bouncer to welcome Rassie. It is down the leg side. Van der Dussen ducks under it.
Rassie van der Dussen walks out to bat next.

OUT! Caught! Three down and we still have close to an hour left for the close! How many more coming? Excellent ball but also a lovely catch from Jos Buttler. Superb comeback here from Jofra. He has the last laugh and got rid of Elgar with a peach. Good length ball pitching on off. It jags back in venomously. Elgar looks to defend but the ball comes back in a long way. It takes the inside edge of his defensive willow and goes over the stumps. Seems like it will race away to the fine leg fence but Jos Buttler dives to his right and takes a very good catch. Archer and Buttler put in an appeal and umpire Gaffaney raises his finger. Bang, bang, bang! The Proteas are effectively 132/3. Any chances of a reminiscence of the 2016 Jo'burg miracle? You never know with Broady and Archer...
FOUR! Done with ease! Not a welcome Jofra would have been looking for. Overpitched on off, Elgar just uses the pace of the ball and strokes it through mid off for an elegant boundary.
First bowling change of the innings and it sees Jofra Archer being brought on. He was not at his best in the first innings, can he make amends in the second?

That is a beauty! In the channel around off. It swings in but straightens after hitting the deck. Du Plessis lunges forward to defend but gets squared up. He is lucky not to edge it as the ball just about misses the outside edge. That is a trademark Broad delivery.
Good length ball outside off, du Plessis leaves it alone.
Faf du Plessis is the new man in.

OUT! Caught! Another wicket which has come down the leg side. A very similar way to how Elgar got out in the first innings. Broad bowls one around the pads, down the leg side. Hamza is cramped for room as he tries to tickle it fine down the leg side. The ball kisses his bat and then the pads and goes to the left of the keeper. Buttler behind the stumps puts in a dive on that side and takes a very good catch. He puts an appeal along with the bowler and the umpire raises his finger. Zubayr does not wait and starts walking back.
Solidly defended now. Good length ball once again the line is the same. Hamza defends it off his back foot towards mid off.
Nicely played. Length delivery close to off pole. Hamza gets on his back foot and punches it to cover.
Broad goes full and on middle and leg, Elgar glances it to mid-wicket.
Length delivery outside off, DE shoulders arms to it to get through the over.
Away from the off pole, Elgar knows that he has already scored 12 runs off the over so there is no need to play that and he calmly leaves it alone.

FOUR! Third boundary off the over! Anderson is not looking like himself here. He now strays down the pads, Elgar flicks it with ease through the square leg fence. The man from fine leg gives it a chase but cannot stop the ball from reaching the fence.
Smart cricket this from Elgar. Anderson pulls his length back and goes to the off stump line. Dean leaves it alone.
FOUR! This one is straight down the ground. Anderson is once again guilty of going too full on off. Elgar gets on his front foot and drives it through mid off for a boundary.
FOUR! Uppish but well placed. Full outside off, Elgar stretches out and lofts his drive over point for a boundary.
Full on off, Hamza blocks it to get through the over.
Around off, Hamza defends it with confidence.

Broad goes around the wicket and darts in on the pads with the angle. Elgar looks to flick but misses. The ball hits his pad and goes down the leg side. Broad goes up in a hopeful appeal but the umpire shakes it away. The batters meanwhile takes a single.
Full and on the pads, Hamza flicks it through mid-wicket and gets a single.
Broad hits the deck hard on off, Zubayr defends it off the back foot.
Fuller on off, Hamza defends it off the front foot.
Beaten! Good length ball outside off, Elgar pokes at the ball to get beaten.

Huge appeal but not out says the umpire. Root does not go for the DRS. Good call in the end as the replays show that it was going to miss the off pole. Coming to the ball, it's a good length ball outside off, Elgar looks to defend but misses as it comes back in a hint. A stifled appeal from England as Buttler grabs the ball low to his left.
On a good length on off, Elgar plays it to point.
On a good length on off, Hamza taps it towards point. The batsmen take a single.
Good length delivery on off, Hamza defends it towards point.
On a good length on middle, Hamza defends it off the back foot.
Full and on the pads, Elgar tucks it to mid-wicket.
Full and on off, defended towards mid off.
Outside off, it is left alone.
Beaten this time! Lands it just outside off and makes it move away from the poke of Elgar.
Good leave this time! Broad goes full just outside off, asking Elgar to drive. Elgar though is not interested as he covers his stumps and lets it be.
Almost dragged on! Broad has his hands on his head. A good length ball around off, Elgar looks to defend but gets an inside edge on the pads.
Outside off, Hamza lets it go.
Good length delivery on off, Elgar defends it towards the off side. The batsmen take a run.
On a length on middle, Elgar flicks it towards the leg side.
Full delivery on middle, Hamza looks to flick but gets it off the inner half of the bat. It goes towards mid-wicket. The batsmen cross ends.
Length delivery on middle, Elgar flicks it through square leg for a run.
On a length on middle, Hamza nudges it towards fine leg for a single.
On a good length on off, Elgar defends it off the front foot.
FOUR! Nicely played! Good length delivery on off, Elgar pokes at it with soft hands and the ball takes an outside edge. It goes between second slip and gully towards third man for a boundary.
Good length delivery on off, Elgar defends it out.
Outside off, Elgar offers no shot to this one.
BEATEN! On a good length and outside off, Elgar looks to defend but misses it.
Outside off, Elgar shoulders arms to this one.
Stuart Broad to bowl from the other end.
Outside off on a good length, it is left alone.
Zubayr Hamza is the next batsman in.

OUT! That is dead plumb!  Waste of a review. A fuller ball around off, Markram looks to flick but misses to get hit on the pads. Massive appeal from the English players and the umpire raises his finger instantly. Markram is not sure. He slowly goes to his partner, they have a word and at the very end, he opts for the DRS. Ultra Edge confirms no involvement of bat. Where is it hitting? Hawk Eye rolls in, wow, crashing on the middle pole. Markram will not enjoy it when he sits down in the dressing room and sees the replays. Not sure how the Protea skipper will react either. Anyways, Anderson has struck for England in the first over, once again. Exactly the kind of start England would've wanted.

Given out LBW. That looks dead plumb to the naked eye. Markram has a word with his partner at the other end and signals the 'T'. No bat there. Here comes the Hawk Eye. Three reds it is. So, a review lost for South Africa in the very first over.
Just behind fuller length outside off, Markram pushes it through cover-point for a couple of runs to get off the mark.
James goes full for the first time on off. Markram pushes it to mid on.
Back of a length on off, Markram defends it with authority by getting right behind this.
Anderson starts with a good length delivery starting on off. It swings away from Markram but he gets behind it and blocks it confidently with a straight bat.

So that is it from the final international game of the year and decade. It is South Africa who take the lead in this 4-match series and start their new tenure under Head Coach Mark Boucher with a win and end the year on a high. The series now moves to the 2nd Test in Cape Town. That match will begin on 3rd January. Join us at 1030 Local (0830 GMT) for that one. Till then, goodbye and have a great end to the year!

For his brilliant batting performance with the bat i the first innings and his record breaking catches behind the stumps Quinton de Kock  has been named the Man of the Match. De Kock says that he walked out and understood the situation. Credits the English bowlers for bowling well on the wicket and troubling them. Quinton admits when he went out he had thought of leaving the balls but says his mind made him do a lot of things other than the plan and he played his shots. On his hand, Quinton says finger is all good but laughs and says that he has keeper's finger and thinks it might be sore tomorrow.

South Africa skipper, Faf du Plessis says that they knew that the last couple ofm months as a Test team had been difficult for them. Says it was a good Test as both the teams toiled hard for this win. Tells everyone is happy and thinks this is a start of a new chapter and theyb are once again improving as a team but is aware that it is going to be a tough task. on Philander's bowling, he says he bowled well but then also says that both the sides bowled really well. Tells Day 3 was good to bat as the pitch started to get a bit soft under heavy clouds. Faf says they knew they had to be patient and knew they could attack and do the damage with the second new ball. Credits Nortje and Rabada for their performance and says that he hopes they can get a couple of more new, young talented bowlers as Philander is moving for pastures new and they need a few bowlers to replace him.

Joe Root, the England skipper. He says that it has been a really tough week for them. Adds that some went down with a bug over the last week but credit to them for giving a tough fight. Says that it has not been long since they have seen such chases from a similar group of players. States that they were in a similar position at Headingley but then they got over the lineAdds they lost the game during the collapse in the first innings but is pleased with a better performance in the second. Credit to South Africa for playing brilliantly. On Archer, he says that he bowled well and he will keep on learning.
Time now for the presentation as we find out what the skippers have to say and who is a named the Man of the Match.

It was a good bowling performance from the hosts in the final innings. They were made to toil hard at the start but they kept their cool and did not lose their patience. It paid off once again as they were able to wrap up the tourists for 268 and win the game with a comfortable margin of 107 runs. Rabada and Nortje were the pick of the bowlers in the second innings. Picking up 4 and 3 wickets respectively.  The lone front line spinner, Keshav Maharaj was good with the ball as well as he picked up the two crucial wickest of Dominic Sibley and the game changing wicket of Ben Stokes. Philander went wicketless in the second innings whereas debutant Pretorius got the crucial wicket of Denly. All-in-all it was a solid bowling performance by the hosts.

England gave a strong reply and got the chase off to a solid start. Openers Burns and Sibley watched off the difficult times with the new ball and mustered a 92-run opening stand before Sibley departed. Denly then joined Burns and the duo continued the good work before Burns fell 16 short of his century. Denly too did not last long but Stokes and Root then once again calmed the nerves but once again there was another English collapse on the cards. At one stage it looked England would take it home with the scorecard reading 222/4, the visitors capitulated and were bowled out for 268.

South Africa started their 2nd innings with a lead of 103 but they once again got off to a torrid start. They were stuttering with the score reading 62/4, with the lead of just 175. But Rassie van der Dussen and nightwatchman Anrich Nortje calmed the hosts nerves with their 91-run stand. Rassie scored his maiden fifty whereas Nortje scored a very crucial 40. Vital contributions from Quinton de Kock and Vernon Philander took the hosts lead to 376. Which was too much for the visitors in the end. Jofra Archer was expensive with the ball but ended up with a 5-wicket haul.

In reply, England had to take the lead to justify their skipper's decision to bowl first. They got off to a good start but a batting collapse from the visitors saw them going from 142/3 to being bowled out for 181. Only 4 batters could go past the score of 20 and thanks to Denly's 50, they managed to have some respectability to the total. Vernon Philander was the star for the Proteas with the ball as his consistent lines and lengths continued to ask questions and he ended up with a 4-fer.

After winning the toss and opting to bowl, Root's controversial decision seemed to be paying off as the hosts were struggling at 111/5 but Quinton de Kock's 95 took the hosts' score to 284 and that proved to be a big turning point. Sam Curran was the star with the ball as he picked up a 4-fer. Broad too ended up with 4 wickets in the first innings.

End of a fascinating Test and what a start we have had to the series. The momentum of the game kept swinging in from here to there right from the first day but in the end, it was the hosts who have held their nerves and played better cricket for the majority part to win the game comfortably in the end and take the lead in this 4-match series.

OUT! TIMBER! You miss I hit says Rabada. And that is that for this game. Brilliant performance from South Africa. Broad was just going after every ball here and this, you might feel that it was coming. Yorker on middle, Broad makes room to play it to the off side but misses it completely. Rabada though does not miss and the ball goes on to hit the middle stump. Rabada finishes with four wickets. SOUTH AFRICA WIN BY 107 RUNS.

Just wide! Full delivery on middle, Broad flicks it uppishly to mid-wicket. Maharaj makes a good effort as he dives in an attempt to catch it but is just wide of him. The fielder runs across from deep square leg and picks it up. Another couple.

EDGY! Good length ball, Broad makes room but Rabada follows him. Stuart looks to cut it but gets an inside edge which goes past the keeper to fine leg. Nortje comes across and cleans it up. Two Taken.
Short ball on middle, Broad stands tall and pulls it through mid-wicket for a couple. Maharaj chases after it and cleans it up.
James Anderson is the last man in.

OUT! Buttler holes out! His counter-attacking approach does not last long and it has to be game, set and match here. South Africa have held their nerves and delivered here. All the main batters are out of here and England are just a wicket away from sealing this game. Back of a length ball on off, Buttler looks to pull but he does not get it off the middle. It hits the upper half of his bat and goes high up in the air. It does not travel the distance and goes towards long on. Dwaine Pretorius there comes in and keeps his eyes on the ball and takes the skier with ease.

SIX! That is a terrific shot from Jos Buttler. Full delivery on off, Buttler clears his one leg and hammers it over long on for a maximum. The umpires checks whether it is a six or a boundary. The replays show that it has landed way over the ropes.
South Africa are just 2 wickets away from sealing this game so the umpires have decided to extend this session.
Good follow-up delivery from Nortje. After dishing out a short delivery, Nortje goes for a full delivery on middle, Broad plays it back to the bowler.
Nasty delivery! Short of a length delivery on middle and off, Broad hops and looks to defend it. It hits the grille of the helmet. Luckily for him, no damage done. That could have really hurt.
Stuart Broad walks out at number 10.

OUT! CAUGHT! Nortje has picked up his third wicket. Brilliant stuff from Anrich and the hosts are just two wickets away from a terrific victory. Back of a length ball from Nortje, Archer looks to push it to the off side but gets a thick outside edge towards first slip. Rassie van der Dussen who is standing there takes a simple catch. Look at the celebrations. They are ecstatic. Once again England have collapsed after giving a tough fight.
BOUNCER! It is bowled around middle. Archer ducks under it.
Back of a length ball on off, Archer pushes it to point.
Good length delivery on middle, Buttler looks to flick but gets a leading edge towards cover. A single taken.
BEATEN! Excellent delivery! Good length ball outside off, Archer looks to defend it but fails to get any bat on it.

FOUR! Off the mark straightaway is Archer! Good length ball outside off, Archer punches it off the back foot to the deep point region. Zubayr Hamza puts in a terrific run from deep point and slides but can only parry it into the fence.
Jofra Archer is the new man in. He needs to hang in there and let Buttler face as many deliveries as possible.

OUT! Caught! Rabada strikes yet another one. The dangerous Curran has also gone now. This is a brilliant ball from Kagiso. Its starts on off and it looks like it will go away with the angle but the ball straightens up after pitching. Curran looks to defend but gets a good outside edge which goes straight to Quinton de Kock behind the stumps. De Kock's 8th catch of the game and he has had a very good Test. 125 more needed for England to win. South Africa just 3 wickets away from a win here.
FOUR! Thrashed. England are looking to counter-attack here. Full delivery outside off, Curran hammers it through covers for a boundary. 250 up for South Africa.
Bowls a bouncer, Sam does well to duck under it. Good take by Quinton de Kock behind the stumps.
BEATEN! On a good length and outside off, Curran looks to defend but misses it.
Played to the point region by the batsman.

SIX! Hammered! Short of a length ball on middle, Buttler rocks on his back foot and pulls it with absolute disdain over the deep square leg region for a biggie. There are two fielders stationed there but it has gone way over the fence.

Good length delivery on middle, Buttler hops to flick it but it seems to have gone off the inside edge, onto the pads towards short leg. The replays show that it has indeed gone off the edge. Luckily for Buttler, it falls wide of the fielder.
FOUR! Audacious! Buttler finally shows his class. Back of a length delivery outside off, Buttler pushes it off the back foot through the extra cover region for a boundary.
On a length on off, Curran defends it to cover and picks up a single.
EDGED AND FOUR! Luck favoring Sam Curran! Good length ball outside off, Curran looks to drive it but hits the outside edge which goes between the guly and the second slip fielder into the fence.
The batsman shows the full face of the bat and defends the ball off the back foot.
Full delivery on middle, Jos looks to flick it but gets a leading edge which goes towards gully. No run.
OHH! On a length on off swinging in, Buttler looks to flick but misses to get hit on the thigh pad.
PLAY AND A MISS! Short of a length delivery outside off, Buttler looks to push it off the back foot but fails to get any bat on it.
BEATEN! Good length ball outside off, Buttler looks to defend it but misses it altogether.

Full delivery down the leg side, Buttler looks to flick it but it seems that it has gone off the pads. De Kock dives and makes a half stop. Quinton looks distraught thinking that it was a drop but the Ultra Edge shows that there was no bat.
Fullish on off, Curran pushes it to mid off.
On a length on off, Sam defends it out onto the pitch.
BEATEN! Excellent bowling from Nortje. He has looked the best bowler for the Proteas. Good length ball outside off, Curran looks to defend it but misses it altogether.
Full delivery on off, Curran looks to flick it but gets an inside edge onto the pads. No run.
Sam Curran is the new man in. He is no walkover with the bat and if he can support Buttler out there, England will be still in with a chance.

OUT! Caught behind! Is this the end of this chase here? Joe Root is out of here and once again the bowling change has done the trick. Nortje with the bat, Nortje with the ball. Nortje winning the game for his side. Anrich steams in and hits the deck hard on off, it is in the corridor of uncertainty. The ball nips away off the deck. Root lunges forward to get a feel of the ball. All he does is get a good, fat outside edge which goes straight into the gloves of Quinton de Kock. Massive blow for the visitors. The South African players are up in celebration and England in troubled waters here. 144 runs more to win and South Africa just 4 wickets away from wrapping this up. Now Buttler and Sam Curran will have to play a gem of an innings here if England are to do the unimaginable. South Africa firmly in the driver's seat here.
Starts with a full delivery outside off tailing in, Root leaves it alone.
Anrich Nortje is back on. 14-3-40-1 are his figures so far.
Back of a length ball on middle, Jos works it to the leg side.
Good length delivery on off, Buttler defends it out to cover.
Full delivery on middle, Root attempts to defend it but it goes off the inside edge to fine leg. A single taken.
Fullish on middle, Root plays it back to the bowler.
On a length on middle, Root defends it out.
FOUR! Classic shot! Back of a length delivery outside off, Root punches it off the back foot with one hand of the bat. It goes through gully for a boundary.

Oh ho! It has gone very dark all of a sudden and the floodlights are on now.

Buttler defends this length ball on middle back to the bowler.
Fullish one outside off, left alone by Buttler.

Outside off, Buttler shoulders arms to this one.
Full delivery swinging away, Jos shoulders arms to this one.

On off swinging in, Root makes a good leave.

BEATEN! Beautiful stuff from Rabada! Good length delivery around off with some swing away. Buttler looks to defend it but goes past the outside edge of the bat. No harm done.

Jos Buttler is the next batsman in. He has a big responsibility in his hands and needs to support his skipper if they are to chase it down. Remember both these players struggled with illness yesterday and Buttler did not even take the field on Day 3.

OUT! Caught! The new ball has done its magic and Faf's decision to take the new ball has taken just two deliveries to do its magic. Full and swinging away from Bairstow. He looks to play it away from his body and ends up getting a thick outside edge which flies to the man at gully. Zubayr Hamza there gets it in an awkward height but he hops and makes it look easy. Looks like he has hurt himself too with the new ball but at this moment it does not matter as South Africa have sent half the English side packing back into the pavilion. Joe Root looks helpless from the other end. Jonny's poor run in red ball cricket continues. 154 runs more needed and South Africa are on fire here.
FOUR! Rabada starts with a poor delivery down the pads. Full delivery on middle, Bairstow whips it beautifully to deep mid-wicket and picks up a boundary.
Faf has opted to take the second new ball as soon as it has become available and Rabada will start with it. Will this decision work out or will it backfire?

OHH! Good length ball around off, Root looks to defend it but gets hit on the pads. It lobs off to Zubayr Hamza at gully who catches it sliding forward. The Proteas appeal but the umpire says no. Good decision in the end as the Hawk Eye shows that the impact was outside off. The South Africans do not think of a review.
On a length on off, Root defends it to point.
Full delivery on middle, Root drives it back to Pretorius.
Good length ball on middle, Root works it to deep square leg and picks up a couple.
Full delivery on middle which kept a little low, Root gets his bat down in time and defends it.

So this is the last over before the new ball is available. It will be interesting to see whether Faf du Plessis opts it straightaway and start attacking with Philander and Rabada or he waits back and lets Maharaj have a few more go with this old cherry. He has been able to grip and turn the ball from the rough and also there have been some uneven bounce on offer.

Ohh! This is going to send chills down the England batting line up. Maharaj bowls it short outside off, Root tries to dab it down towards third man but fails to do so. Guess why? Because the ball has stayed low and refused to bounce. Lucky for Root that was not on the stumps.

OHH! Good length ball on middle and leg, Root moves towards the off side and looks to flick it but misses. It is hit on the pads and rolls to the leg side. Pretorius appeals but nothing from the umpire. A leg bye taken.
Length outside off, left alone by Root.

On middle, defended out.
Loopy delivery on middle, Jonny defends it back to the bowler.
Outside off, left alone.
The batsman has defended it by getting right behind the line of the delivery.
FOUR! Poor bowling this though! Full delivery on the pads, Root just helps it on its way to the backward square leg for a boundary. Keshav Maharaj comes, slides but fails to stop it.

BEATEN! Brilliant stuff from Pretorius! Good length ball around off, angling away from the batsman. Root looks to defend it but misses it. Suddenly after the wicket the ball has started doing something off the pitch.
Things are now happening after that wicket! Good length ball on middle, Root looks to defend it but hits him around the box. Looks fine to continue.

Jonny Bairstow replaces Ben Stokes out in the middle. A very crucial innings for him. He has been out of runs in this format and needs to score if he wants to keep his place in the playing XI as Ollie Pope is fit again and waiting on his heels.

OUT! Chopped on! Maharaj is in cloud 9, South African players are on cloud 9! England's crisis man, the miracle man of Headingley is out of here. Massive wicket in this game. No Ben Magic here in Centurion as Maharaj has got the king-sized wicket of Ben Stokes. Maharaj bowls it slightly short but on the rough. It puts Ben Stokes in two minds, whether to play at it or let it go. He tries to dab it down towards third man but the ball is too close to do it. The ball turns in a bit as well. It hits the glove and goes onto hit the stumps. The hosts are up in joy and the home fans are loving it too. Faf is up and pumping and this match has got another turn to it. 172 runs more needed and one might feel South Africa will have their energies up as they have got the big fish here. No Big Ben show so is this the end of this chase? England still have 6 wickets and their skipper is still out there in the middle but has Keshav delivered the body blow in the form of Stokes' wicket?
Flatter delivery on middle and leg, Stokes works it to the leg side.

On middle, defended to mid on off the back foot.

Fullish on middle and leg, Stokes defends it to the leg side.
Back of a length delivery on middle, Stokes works it to mid-wicket.
On a length on middle, Stokes flicks it through square leg. The batsmen pick up a couple.
Change from both the ends. Dwaine Pretorius is back on. He has a wicket to his name, can he strike another one before the new ball is available?
FOUR! England are turning it on at Centurion. Short delivery outside off, Root goes on his back foot and punches it through covers for a boundary. 200 up for England.
Flatter delivery on middle and leg, Stokes looks to flick it but misses to get hit on the pads. The ball rolls to square leg and the batters steal a leg bye.

On middle, defended back to the bowler.
Loopy ball on off, Stokes defends it back to the bowler.

Short ball outside off, Root defends it out.

We are back for the second session. The South African players are out in the middle. Joe Root and Ben Stokes will resume their innings for England. Vernon Philander will start the proceedings for the second session.
... Day 4, Session 2 ...

So 50 runs and 2 wickets came in this session. England need further 205 runs to win. South Africa need 7 wickets. What do we have in store for the second session? Can South Africa take advantage or will Stokes and Root take the tourists out of troubled waters? Join us after the break to find out.

England started off the day cautiously. They took the defensive approach. Burns and Denly ate some deliveries and scored 18 runs before Burns departed. Denly too did not last long after it. The visitors have two of their best batters in their captain Joe Root and vice-captain Ben Stokes out in the middle. The pair managed to watch out the remaining time before Lunch and ensured that they do not have any further casualties heading into the break. The onus will be on this pair to build a big partnership.

Another evenly poised session in this Test but it will be South Africa who will be the happier of the two sides. The Proteas bowlers were sub-par with the ball on Day 3 but they started off well on Day 4. Rabada and Philander built pressure but it was Nortje and Pretorius who bore the fruit of that. The pair managed to get rid of a very well-set Burns and after a while even sent Denly packing. The hosts have 205 runs to play with and need 7 wickets to win this Test.

Ben Stokes is the new man in. Can he repeat his Headingley heroics?

OUT! LBW! Umpire's call. The ball is just clipping the leg pole but it is enough for Denly to walk back. The pressure the opening bowlers built is starting to pay off as the new bowlers are getting the breakthrough. A wicket that South Africa wanted. A wicket that South Africa have got. Both the well-set batsmen are out of here and South Africa on top here. Very good bowling from Pretorius. Good length ball pitching around off and coming back in. Denly looks to flick it across the line but misses. There is a huge appeal from the Proteas players and the umpire agrees with him and raises the finger. Joe Denly has a word with his skipper and then signals the 'T'. Replay rolls in and Hawk Eye shows that the pitching is not an issue. The impact is in line as well and the ball is clipping the leg pole. England retain their review but cannot overturn the on-field umpire's decision and England are in trouble here. They need 218 runs more to win but now have just the 7 wickets in hand.

Denly has been adjudged LBW! It looks very close and Denly after having a word with Root has taken it upstairs. The on-field call is out so all it needs to do is just clip the stump for South Africa to get their second wicket of the day.

OUT! Caught! The bowling change has done the wonders for the hosts. Nortje strikes in his second ball of the over. Big, big wicket for the Proteas and this could be the wicket that puts the South Africans back in the driver's seat. Nortje goes short and it is well directed as well as it is very close to the body. The ball hurries onto Burns. He looks to pull it but he is very late in his shot. The ball hits the upper half of the bat and goes high in the air. It goes towards mid on. Rabada's eyes lit up looking at that but he does not lose his composure and he takes a good, simple catch. Burns' innings comes to an end. He misses out on a hundred but more importantly he was set and had to bat at least till Lunch. This changes the dynamics of the game here. First wicket of the day. South Africa need another 8 to win this. England need further 237. The match is back in balance.

Day 4 is all set to begin! England need 255 to win this Test and have 9 wickets in hand to do so. Rory Burns and Joe Denly make their way out to the middle. Vernon Philander will start the proceedings.

One of the two Boxing Day Tests is done. It was the hosts, Australia who decimated New Zealand. Where is the second Boxing Day Test heading? This one is evenly poised. Both the sides have a chance to win it and no one knows which way this game is heading. It has been a topsy-turvy game so far. The hosts need 9 wickets and are aware of England's habit of collapsing so they will still fancy themselves. The visitors, on the other hand, don't need to look too far away for inspiration as it was very recently that they chased down a mammoth total at Headingley. If that is not enough, the tourists must be aware of the hosts' behavior of tumbling under pressure. It's the last Sunday of 2019 and we are up for an exciting finish of international cricket for the year. Who are you backing to win this? Welcome to the coverage of Day 4 of this fascinating 1st Test between South Africa and England.

So 255 runs more is what England require. South Africa need 9 wickets to win this game. Nobody knows who is on top as both the teams at the end of the day have an equal chance to take the lead in this series opener. The pitch looked good to bat on Day 3 and looking at it, all the criticism Joe Root got for bowling first is starting to backfire. What do we have in store on Day 4? It might just be the last day of this Test and can go either way. Join us on Sunday, 29th December at 1000 local (0800 GMT) as we inch closer to the climax of this fascinating Test. Is it the pitch or is there some issue with the mentality? As just like England, South African bowlers too looked out of sorts. They were not consistent with their lines and lengths and struggled to find their rhythm. The bowlers were not aided by some sloppy fielding as Rassie van der Dussen put down Burns who is making him and the hosts pay. They did manage to break the opening stand, courtesy of their spinner, Keshav Maharaj. But all-in-all, the hosts need to sort themselves up and come back stronger if they are to avoid an unexpected defeat in this Test.

But as has been the story of this Test so far, England got back up after being down and out for the majority of the day. Sibley and Burns laid the foundation of the chase. The duo added a 92-run stand for the opening wicket to give the English fans some hope. Burns got to his fifty and is still out there looking very good. He has been solid in his approach and has made most of the chance he got when Rassie van der Dussen put him down on 20. His opening partner Dominic Sibley got out against the run of play but Joe Denly then joined Burns out in the middle and the duo ensured that the visitors did not have any further damage before Stumps.

Jofra Archer was the pick of the bowlers as he ended up with a 5-fer but he was expensive. The other English bowlers looked jaded, out of ideas and tired. A couple of players, namely Buttler and Root struggled with illness as well. And with a target of 376 to chase, it looked like the day and the match belonged to South Africa.
